# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dns-security-extensions
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] An alternative to DoH is the DNS over TLS (DoT) protocol, a similar standard for encrypting DNS queries, differing only in the methods used for encryption and delivery.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Based on privacy and security, whether either protocol is superior is a matter of debate, while others argue that the merits of either depend on the specific use case.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] DoH is a proposed standard, published as RFC 8484 (October 2018) by the IETF.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] It uses HTTPS, and supports the *wire format* DNS response data, as returned in existing UDP responses, in an HTTPS payload with the MIME type *application/dns-message*.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] The underlying HTTP layer can be any version of HTTP, though HTTP/2 is the *recommended* minimum.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] If HTTP/2 is used, the server may also use HTTP/2 server push to send values that it anticipates the client may find useful in advance.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Even though the IETF has published RFC 8484 as a proposed standard and companies are experimenting with it, the IETF has yet to determine how it should best be implemented.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] The IETF is evaluating a number of approaches for how best to deploy DoH and has established a working group, Adaptive DNS Discovery (ADD), to do this work and develop a consensus.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Since DoH cannot be used under some circumstances, like captive portals, web browsers like Firefox can be configured to fall back to insecure DNS.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] The de facto DoH URL is *https://host_name/dns-query*.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Oblivious DNS over HTTPS (ODoH) is an experimental standard, published as RFC 9230 (June 2022) by the IETF, proposing a protocol extension to ensure no single DoH server is aware of both the client's IP address and the content of their DNS queries and responses.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] This is an application of a security principle called decoupling or privacy partitioning.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] A different protocol with the same name (Oblivious DoH) was originally developed as Oblivious DNS (ODNS) by researchers at Princeton University and the University of Chicago as an extension to unencrypted DNS, before DoH itself was standardized and widely deployed.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Apple and Cloudflare subsequently deployed the technology in the context of DoH, as Oblivious DoH (ODoH).
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] In ODoH and ODNS, all DNS requests and responses are routed via a proxy, hiding the client's address from the resolver.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Requests and responses are encrypted to hide their contents from the proxy, and only the resolver can decrypt the requests, and the client the responses.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Thus, the proxy knows the client address and resolver but not the request, and the resolver knows the proxy and request but not the client address, preventing the client address being linked to the query, unless both the proxy and resolver servers collude.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Another protocol, Oblivious HTTP, uses similar architectural principles for HTTP requests.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] DoH is used for recursive DNS resolution by DNS resolvers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Resolvers (*DoH clients*) must have access to a DoH server hosting a query endpoint.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Apple's iOS 14 and macOS 11 released in late 2020 support both DoH and DoT protocols.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] In iOS, the protocols can be used via configuration profiles.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] In November 2019, Microsoft announced plans to implement support for encrypted DNS protocols in Microsoft Windows, beginning with DoH.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] In May 2020, Microsoft released Windows 10 Insider Preview Build 19628 that included initial support for DoH along with instructions on how to enable it via registry and command line interface.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Windows 10 Insider Preview Build 20185 added a graphical user interface for specifying a DoH resolver.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] DoH support is not included in Windows 10 21H2.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Android 11 onwards supports DNS over HTTP/3 (DoH3) if a July 2022 system update is installed.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] BIND 9, an open source DNS resolver from Internet Systems Consortium added native support for DoH in version 9.17.10.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] DNSdist, an open source DNS proxy/load balancer from PowerDNS, added native support for DoH in version 1.4.0 in April 2019.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Unbound, an open source DNS resolver created by NLnet Labs, has supported DoH since version 1.12.0, released in October 2020.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] It first implemented support for DNS encryption using the alternative DoT protocol much earlier, starting with version 1.4.14, released in December 2011.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Unbound runs on most operating systems, including distributions of Linux, BSD, MacOS, and Windows.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] DNS over HTTPS is available in Google Chrome 83 or later for Windows, Linux, and macOS, configurable via the settings page.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] When enabled, and the operating system is configured with a supported DNS server, Chrome will upgrade DNS queries to be encrypted.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] It is also possible to manually specify a preset or custom DoH server to use within the user interface.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] In September 2020, Google Chrome for Android began staged rollout of DNS over HTTPS.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Users can configure a custom resolver or disable DNS over HTTPS in settings.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Google Chrome has five DNS-over-HTTPS providers pre-configured, which are Google Public DNS, Cloudflare's 1.1.1.1, Quad9's 9.9.9.9, NextDNS, and CleanBrowsing.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Microsoft Edge supports DNS over HTTPS, configurable via the settings page.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] When enabled, and the operating system is configured with a supported DNS server, Edge will upgrade DNS queries to be encrypted.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] In 2018, Mozilla partnered with Cloudflare to deliver DoH for Firefox users that enable it (known as Trusted Recursive Resolver).
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] On February 25, 2020, Firefox started enabling DNS over HTTPS for all US-based users, relying on Cloudflare's resolver by default.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Opera supports DoH, configurable via the browser settings page.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] By default, DNS queries are sent to Cloudflare servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Brave implemented DNS over HTTPS (DoH) by default for its desktop browser in version 1.4, released in April 2020, as part of its broader privacy-focused features to encrypt DNS queries and prevent third-party eavesdropping or manipulation.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] DNS over HTTPS server implementations are already available free of charge by some public DNS providers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] DoH can impede analysis and monitoring of DNS traffic for cybersecurity purposes; the 2019 DDoS worm Godlua used DoH to mask connections to its command-and-control server.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] In January 2021, NSA warned enterprises against using external DoH resolvers because they prevent DNS query filtering, inspection, and audit.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Instead, NSA recommends configuring enterprise-owned DoH resolvers and blocking all known external DoH resolvers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] DoH has been used to bypass parental controls which operate at the (unencrypted) standard DNS level; However, there are DNS providers that offer filtering and parental controls along with support for DoH by operating DoH servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] In response to the criticism, the ISPA apologized and withdrew the nomination.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] Mozilla subsequently stated that DoH will not be used by default in the British market until further discussion with relevant stakeholders, but stated that it "would offer real security benefits to UK citizens".
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-https] In July 2020, iYouPort, the University of Maryland, and the Great Firewall Report, reported that the Great Firewall (GFW) by the Chinese government blocks TLS connections using the encrypted SNI extension in China.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] While DNS over TLS is applicable to any DNS transaction, it was first standardized for use between stub or forwarding resolvers and recursive resolvers, in RFC 7858 in May of 2016.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] Subsequent IETF efforts specify the use of DoT between recursive and authoritative servers ("Authoritative DNS over TLS" or "ADoT") and a related implementation between authoritative servers (Zone Transfer-over-TLS or "xfr-over-TLS").
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] BIND supports DoT connections as of version 9.17.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] Earlier versions offered DoT capability by proxying through stunnel.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] Unbound has supported DNS over TLS since 22 January 2023.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] Unwind has supported DoT since 29 January 2023.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] With Android Pie's support for DNS over TLS, some ad blockers now support using the encrypted protocol as a relatively easy way to access their services versus any of the various work-around methods typically used such as VPNs and proxy servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] Android clients running Android Pie or newer support DNS over TLS and will use it by default if the network infrastructure, for example the ISP, supports it.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] In April 2018, Google announced that Android Pie will include support for DNS over TLS, allowing users to set a DNS server phone-wide on both Wi-Fi and mobile connections, an option that was historically only possible on rooted devices or by using VPNService API.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] DNSDist, from PowerDNS, also announced support for DNS over TLS in version 1.3.0.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] Linux and Windows users can use DNS over TLS as a client through the NLnet Labs stubby daemon or Knot Resolver.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] Alternatively they may install getdns-utils to use DoT directly with the getdns_query tool.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] The unbound DNS resolver by NLnet Labs also supports DNS over TLS.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] Apple's iOS 14 introduced OS-level support for DNS over TLS (and DNS over HTTPS). iOS does not allow manual configuration of DoT servers, and requires the use of a third-party application to make configuration changes.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] systemd-resolved is a Linux-only implementation that can be configured to use DNS over TLS, by editing `/etc/systemd/resolved.conf` and enabling the setting `DNSOverTLS`.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] Most major Linux distributions have systemd installed by default.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] DNS over TLS was first implemented in a public recursive resolver by Quad9 in 2017.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] Other recursive resolver operators such as Google and Cloudflare followed suit in subsequent years, and now it is a broadly-supported feature generally available in most large recursive resolvers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] DoT can impede analysis and monitoring of DNS traffic for cybersecurity purposes.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] DoT has been used to bypass parental controls which operate at the (unencrypted) standard DNS level; However, there are DNS providers that offer filtering and parental controls along with support for both DoT and DoH.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] In that scenario, DNS queries are checked against block lists once they are received by the provider rather than prior to leaving the user's router.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] As with any communication, encryption of DNS requests by itself does not protect privacy.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] It protects against third-party observers, but does not guarantee what the endpoints do with the (then decrypted) data.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] DoT clients do not necessarily directly query any authoritative name servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] The client may rely on the DoT server using traditional (port 53 or 853) queries to finally reach authoritative servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] Thus, DoT does not qualify as an end-to-end encrypted protocol, only hop-to-hop encrypted and only if DNS over TLS is used consistently.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] DNS over HTTPS (DoH) is a similar protocol standard for encrypting DNS queries, differing only in the methods used for encryption and delivery from DoT.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] On the basis of privacy and security, whether or not a superior protocol exists among the two is a matter of controversial debate, while others argue the merits of either depend on the specific use case.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-over-tls] DNSCrypt is another network protocol that authenticates and encrypts DNS traffic, although it was never proposed to the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) with a Request for Comments (RFC).
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] A Domain Name System server translates a human-readable domain name (such as `example.com`) into a numerical IP address that is used to route communications between nodes.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] Normally if the server does not know a requested translation it will ask another server, and the process continues recursively.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] To increase performance, a server will typically remember (cache) these translations for a certain amount of time.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] This means if it receives another request for the same translation, it can reply without needing to ask any other servers, until that cache expires.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] When a DNS server has received a false translation and caches it for performance optimization, it is considered *poisoned*, and it supplies the false data to clients.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] If a DNS server is poisoned, it may return an incorrect IP address, diverting traffic to another computer (often an attacker's).
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] Normally, a networked computer uses a DNS server provided by an Internet service provider (ISP) or the computer user's organization.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] DNS servers are used in an organization's network to improve resolution response performance by caching previously obtained query results.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] Poisoning attacks on a single DNS server can affect the users serviced directly by the compromised server or those serviced indirectly by its downstream server(s) if applicable.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] To perform a cache poisoning attack, the attacker exploits flaws in the DNS software.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] A server should correctly validate DNS responses to ensure that they are from an authoritative source (for example by using DNSSEC); otherwise the server might end up caching the incorrect entries locally and serve them to other users that make the same request.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] This attack can be used to redirect users from a website to another site of the attacker's choosing.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] For example, an attacker spoofs the IP address DNS entries for a target website on a given DNS server and replaces them with the IP address of a server under their control.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] The attacker then creates files on the server under their control with names matching those on the target server.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] These files usually contain malicious content, such as computer worms or viruses.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] A user whose computer has referenced the poisoned DNS server gets tricked into accepting content coming from a non-authentic server and unknowingly downloads the malicious content.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] This technique can also be used for phishing attacks, where a fake version of a genuine website is created to gather personal details such as bank and credit/debit card details.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] The vulnerability of systems to DNS cache poisoning goes beyond its immediate effects as it can open users up to further risks such as phishing, malware injections, denial of service, and website hijacking due to system vulnerabilities.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] Various methods, ranging from the use of social engineering tactics to the exploitation of weaknesses present in the DNS server software, can lead to these attacks.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] In the following variants, the entries for the server ns.target.example would be poisoned and redirected to the attacker's name server at IP address *w.x.y.z*.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] These attacks assume that the name server for target.example is ns.target.example.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] To accomplish the attacks, the attacker must force the target DNS server to make a request for a domain controlled by one of the attacker's nameservers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] The first variant of DNS cache poisoning involves redirecting the name server of the attacker's domain to the name server of the target domain, then assigning that name server an IP address specified by the attacker.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] DNS server's request: what are the address records for subdomain.attacker.example?
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] A vulnerable server would cache the additional A-record (IP address) for ns.target.example, allowing the attacker to resolve queries to the entire target.example domain.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] The second variant of DNS cache poisoning involves redirecting the nameserver of another domain unrelated to the original request to an IP address specified by the attacker.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] A vulnerable server would cache the unrelated authority information for target.example's NS-record (nameserver entry), allowing the attacker to resolve queries to the entire target.example domain.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] Many cache poisoning attacks against DNS servers can be prevented by being less trusting of the information passed to them by other DNS servers, and ignoring any DNS records passed back that are not directly relevant to the query.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] For example, versions of BIND 9.5.0-P1 and above perform these checks.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] Source port randomization for DNS requests, combined with the use of cryptographically secure random numbers for selecting both the source port and the 16-bit cryptographic nonce, can greatly reduce the probability of successful DNS race attacks.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] However, when routers, firewalls, proxies, and other gateway devices perform network address translation (NAT), or more specifically, port address translation (PAT), they may rewrite source ports in order to track connection state.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] When modifying source ports, PAT devices may remove source port randomness implemented by nameservers and stub resolvers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] Secure DNS (DNSSEC) uses cryptographic digital signatures signed with a trusted public key certificate to determine the authenticity of data.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] DNSSEC can counter cache poisoning attacks.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] In 2010 DNSSEC was implemented in the Internet root zone servers, but needs to be deployed on all top level domain servers as well.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] The DNSSEC readiness of these is shown in the list of Internet top-level domains.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] As of 2020, all of the original TLDs support DNSSEC, as do country code TLDs of most large countries, but many country-code TLDs still do not.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] Many second-level domains also do not support DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] This kind of attack can be mitigated at the transport layer or application layer by performing end-to-end validation once a connection is established.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] A common example of this is the use of Transport Layer Security and digital signatures.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] For example, by using HTTPS (the secure version of HTTP), users may check whether the server's digital certificate is valid and belongs to a website's expected owner.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] Similarly, the secure shell remote login program checks digital certificates at endpoints (if known) before proceeding with the session.
[src:dns-security-extensions/dns-spoofing] For applications that download updates automatically, the application can embed a copy of the signing certificate locally and validate the signature stored in the software update against the embedded certificate.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The **Domain Name System Security Extensions** (**DNSSEC**) is a suite of extension specifications by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) for securing data exchanged in the Domain Name System (DNS) in Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The protocol provides cryptographic authentication of data, authenticated denial of existence, and data integrity, but not availability or confidentiality.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of 2025, DNSSEC deployment is spotty.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The original design of the Domain Name System did not include any security features.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] It was conceived only as a scalable distributed system.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) attempt to add security, while maintaining backward compatibility.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] RFC 3833 of 2004 documents some of the known threats to the DNS, and their solutions in DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC was designed to protect applications using DNS from accepting forged or manipulated DNS data, such as that created by DNS cache poisoning.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] All answers from DNSSEC protected zones are digitally signed.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] By checking the digital signature, a DNS resolver is able to check if the information is identical (i.e. unmodified and complete) to the information published by the zone owner and served on an authoritative DNS server.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC *does not* provide confidentiality of data; in particular, all DNSSEC responses are authenticated but not encrypted.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC *does not* protect against DoS attacks directly, though it indirectly provides some benefit (because signature checking allows the use of potentially untrustworthy parties).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Other standards (not DNSSEC) are used to secure bulk data (such as a DNS zone transfer) sent between DNS servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As documented in RFC 4367, some users and developers make false assumptions about DNS names, such as assuming that a company's common name plus ".com" is always its domain name.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC cannot protect against false assumptions; it can only authenticate that the data is truly from or not available from the domain owner.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DNSSEC specifications (called *DNSSEC-bis*) describe the current DNSSEC protocol in great detail.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] With the publication of these new RFCs (March 2005), an earlier RFC, RFC 2535 has become obsolete.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The full set of RFCs that specify DNSSEC are collected in RFC 9364, which is also BCP 237.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of March 2026, DNSSEC is only operational in 83 (45%) of country code top-level domains.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] ICANN made DNSSEC mandatory for new generic top-level domains in 2014.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Verisign reported about 5% adoption in .net second-level domains and about 4% in .com.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Second-level domain adoption exceeds 50% in .nl (Netherlands), .cz (Czech Republic), .no (Norway), .se (Sweden), and .nu (Niue, but used to sound like "new").
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of 2023, major domains like google.com, amazon.com, and microsoft.com were unsigned.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC works by digitally signing records for DNS lookup using public-key cryptography.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The correct DNSKEY record is authenticated via a chain of trust, starting with a set of verified public keys for the DNS root zone which is the trusted third party.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Domain owners generate their own keys, and upload them using their DNS control panel at their domain-name registrar, which in turn pushes the keys via secDNS to the zone operator (e.g., Verisign for .com) who signs and publishes them in DNS.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS is implemented by the use of several resource records.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Contains the DNSSEC signature for a record set.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS resolvers verify the signature with a public key, stored in a DNSKEY record.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Contains the public key that a DNS resolver uses to verify DNSSEC signatures in RRSIG records.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] References a DNSKEY record in the sub-delegated zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DS record is placed in the parent zone along with the delegating NS records.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Contains a link to the next record name in the zone and lists the record types that exist for the record's name.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS resolvers use NSEC records to verify the non-existence of a record name and type as part of DNSSEC validation.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Contains links to the next record name in the zone (in hashed name sorting order) and lists the record types that exist for the name covered by the hash value in the first label of the NSEC3 record's own name.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] These records can be used by resolvers to verify the non-existence of a record name and type as part of DNSSEC validation.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] NSEC3 records are similar to NSEC records, but NSEC3 uses cryptographically hashed record names to avoid the enumeration of the record names in a zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Authoritative DNS servers use this record to calculate and determine which NSEC3 records to include in responses to DNSSEC requests for non-existing names/types.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] When DNSSEC is used, each answer to a DNS lookup contains an RRSIG DNS record, in addition to the record type that was requested.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The RRSIG record is a digital signature of the answer DNS resource record set.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The digital signature is verified by locating the correct public key found in a DNSKEY record.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The NSEC and NSEC3 records are used to provide cryptographic evidence of the non-existence of any Resource Record (RR).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DS record is used in the authentication of DNSKEYs in the lookup procedure using the chain of trust.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] NSEC and NSEC3 records are used for robust resistance against spoofing.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC was designed to be extensible so that as attacks are discovered against existing algorithms, new ones can be introduced in a backward-compatible fashion as described in RFC 8624.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] From the results of a DNS lookup, a security-aware DNS resolver can determine whether the authoritative name server for the domain being queried supports DNSSEC, whether the answer it receives is secure, and whether there is some sort of error.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The lookup procedure is different for recursive name servers such as those of many ISPs, and for stub resolvers such as those included by default in mainstream operating systems.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Microsoft Windows uses a stub resolver, and Windows Server 2008 R2 and Windows 7 in particular use a non-validating but DNSSEC-aware stub resolver.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Using the chain of trust model, a Delegation Signer (DS) record in a parent domain (DNS zone) can be used to verify a DNSKEY record in a subdomain, which can then contain other DS records to verify further subdomains.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Say that a recursive resolver such as an ISP name server wants to get the IP addresses (A record and/or AAAA records) of the domain "www.example.com".
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] When the resolver receives an answer via the normal DNS lookup process, it then checks to make sure that the answer is correct.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Ideally, the security-aware resolver would start with verifying the DS and DNSKEY records at the DNS root.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Then it would use the DS records for the "com" top-level domain found at the root to verify the DNSKEY records in the "com" zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] From there, it would see if there is a DS record for the "example.com" subdomain in the "com" zone, and if there were, it would then use the DS record to verify a DNSKEY record found in the "example.com" zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Finally, it would verify the RRSIG record found in the answer for the A records for "www.example.com".
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] There are several exceptions to the above example.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] First, if "example.com" does not support DNSSEC, there will be no RRSIG record in the answer and there will not be a DS record for "example.com" in the "com" zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] If there is a DS record for "example.com", but no RRSIG record in the reply, something is wrong and maybe a man in the middle attack is going on, stripping the DNSSEC information and modifying the A records.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Or, it could be a broken security-oblivious name server along the way that stripped the DO flag bit from the query or the RRSIG record from the answer.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Next, it may be that there is not a domain name named "www.example.com", in which case instead of returning a RRSIG record in the answer, there will be either an NSEC record or an NSEC3 record.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] These are "next secure" records that allow the resolver to prove that a domain name does not exist.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The NSEC/NSEC3 records have RRSIG records, which can be verified as above.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Finally, it may be that the "example.com" zone implements DNSSEC, but either the "com" zone or the root zone do not, creating an "island of security" which needs to be validated in some other way.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of 15 July 2010, deployment of DNSSEC to root is completed.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The .com domain was signed with valid security keys and the secure delegation was added to the root zone on 1 April 2011.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] A *validating stub resolver* can also potentially perform its own signature validation by setting the Checking Disabled (CD) bit in its query messages.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] A validating stub resolver uses the CD bit to perform its own recursive authentication.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Using such a validating stub resolver gives the client end-to-end DNS security for domains implementing DNSSEC, even if the Internet service provider or the connection to them is not trusted.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Non-validating stub resolvers must rely on external DNSSEC validation services, such as those controlled by the user's Internet service provider or a public recursive name server, and the communication channels between itself and those name servers, using methods such as DNS over TLS.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] To be able to prove that a DNS answer is correct, one needs to know at least one key or DS record that is correct from sources other than the DNS.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] These starting points are known as **trust anchors** and are typically obtained with the operating system or via some other trusted source.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] When DNSSEC was originally designed, it was thought that the only trust anchor that would be needed was for the DNS root.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The root anchors were first published on 15 July 2010.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] An *authentication chain* is a series of linked DS and DNSKEY records, starting with a trust anchor to the authoritative name server for the domain in question.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Without a complete authentication chain, an answer to a DNS lookup cannot be securely authenticated.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] To limit replay attacks, there are not only the normal DNS TTL values for caching purposes, but additional timestamps in RRSIG records to limit the validity of a signature.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Unlike TTL values which are relative to when the records were sent, the timestamps are absolute.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This means that all security-aware DNS resolvers must have clocks that are fairly closely in sync, say to within a few minutes.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] These timestamps imply that a zone must regularly be re-signed and re-distributed to secondary servers, or the signatures will be rejected by validating resolvers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC involves many different keys, stored both in DNSKEY records, and from other sources to form trust anchors.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In order to allow for replacement keys, a **key rollover** scheme is required.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Typically, this involves first rolling out new keys in new DNSKEY records, in addition to the existing old keys.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Then, when it is safe to assume that the time to live values have caused the caching of old keys to have passed, these new keys can be used.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Finally, when it is safe to assume that the caching of records using the old keys have expired, the old DNSKEY records can be deleted.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This process is more complicated for things such as the keys to trust anchors, such as at the root, which may require an update of the operating system.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Keys in DNSKEY records can be used for two different things and typically different DNSKEY records are used for each.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] First, there are **key signing keys** (KSK) which are used to sign other DNSKEY records containing **zone signing keys** (ZSK), which are used to sign other records.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Since the ZSKs are under complete control and use by one particular DNS zone, they can be switched more easily and more often.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As a result, ZSKs can be much shorter than KSKs and still offer the same level of protection while reducing the size of the RRSIG/DNSKEY records.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] When a new KSK is created, the DS record must be transferred to the parent zone and published there.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DS records use a message digest of the KSK instead of the complete key in order to keep the size of the records small.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This is helpful for zones such as the .com domain, which are very large.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The procedure to update DS keys in the parent zone is also simpler than earlier DNSSEC versions that required DNSKEY records to be in the parent zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] A closely related principle is that of **Algorithm rollover**, this involves migrating a zone from one signing Algorithm to another.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] A good example of this would be migrating from Algorithm 8 (RSA/SHA-256) to Algorithm 13 (ECDSA/SHA-256).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Several ccTLD's have already migrated including .at, .br, .cz, .ch, .fr, .ie, .nl and .ph.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Verisign migrated .com, .net and .edu to Algorithm 13 in late 2023.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The migration of the root domain from Algorithm 8 to Algorithm 13 is currently in planning as of early 2024.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS-based Authentication of Named Entities (DANE) is an IETF working group with the goal of developing protocols and techniques that allow Internet applications to establish cryptographically secured communications with TLS, DTLS, SMTP, and S/MIME based on DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The new protocols will enable additional assurances and constraints for the traditional model based on public key infrastructure.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] They will also enable domain holders to assert certificates for themselves, without reference to third-party certificate authorities.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Support for DNSSEC stapled certificates was enabled in Google Chrome 14, but was later removed.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] For Mozilla Firefox, support was provided by an add-on up to Firefox 56, while native support was proposed but ultimately rejected.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS is a critical and fundamental Internet service, yet in 1990 Steve Bellovin discovered serious security flaws in it.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Research into securing it began, and progressed dramatically when his paper was made public in 1995.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The initial RFC 2065 was published by the IETF in 1997, and initial attempts to implement that specification led to a revised (and believed fully workable) specification in 1999 as IETF RFC 2535.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Plans were made to deploy DNSSEC based on RFC 2535.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Unfortunately, the IETF RFC 2535 specification had very significant problems scaling up to the full Internet; by 2001 it became clear that this specification was unusable for large networks.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In normal operation DNS servers often get out of sync with their parents.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This isn't usually a problem, but when DNSSEC is enabled, this out-of-sync data could have the effect of a serious self-created denial of service.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Also, public key changes could have absurd effects; for example, if the ".com" zone changed its public key, it would have to send 22 million records (because it would need to update all of the signatures in all of its children).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Thus, DNSSEC as defined in RFC 2535 could not scale up to the Internet.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The IETF fundamentally modified DNSSEC, which is called *DNSSEC-bis* when necessary to distinguish it from the original DNSSEC approach of RFC 2535.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This new version uses "delegation signer (DS) resource records" to provide an additional level of indirection at delegation points between a parent and child zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In the new approach, when a child's master public key changes, instead of having six messages for every record in the child, there is one simple message: the child sends the new public key to its parent (signed, of course).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Parents simply store one master public key for each child; this is much more practical.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This means that a little data is pushed to the parent, instead of massive amounts of data being exchanged between the parent and children.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This does mean that clients have to do a little more work when verifying keys.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] More specifically, verifying a DNS zone's KEY RRset requires two signature verification operations instead of the one required by RFC 2535 (there is no impact on the number of signatures verified for other types of RRsets).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Most view this as a small price to pay, since it makes DNSSEC deployment more practical.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The new version is published in RFC4033-4035.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In January 2024, a "KeyTrap" denial-of-service attack was announced for all specification-respecting DNSSEC resolvers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DNSSEC specification (RFC4033-4035) specifies that a resolver, when receiving a signed packet from the upstream, should try *all* keys with the correct "tag" on *all* signatures until one of the combinations successfully verifies.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] By putting many keys with the same "tag" and many signatures corresponding to that "tag" in a packet, the researchers can slow down a resolver by a factor of 2 million.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In response, resolvers began to place limits on the amount of verification errors, key tag collisions, and hash calculations.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Cryptographically proving the absence of a domain requires signing the response to every query for a non-existent domain.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This is not a problem for online signing servers, which keep their keys available online.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] However, DNSSEC was designed around using offline computers to sign records so that zone-signing-keys could be kept in cold storage.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This represents a problem when trying to authenticate responses to queries for non-existent domains since it is impossible to pre-generate a response to every possible hostname query.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The initial solution was to create NSEC records for every pair of domains in a zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Thus if a client queried for a record at the non-existent `k.example.com`, the server would respond with an NSEC record stating that nothing exists between `a.example.com` and `z.example.com`.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] However, this leaks more information about the zone than traditional unauthenticated NXDOMAIN errors because it exposes the existence of real domains.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The NSEC3 records (RFC 5155) were created as an alternative which hashes the name instead of listing them directly.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Over time, advancements in hashing using GPUs and dedicated hardware meant that NSEC3 responses could be cheaply brute forced using offline dictionary attacks.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] NSEC5 has been proposed to allow authoritative servers to sign NSEC responses without having to keep a private key that can be used to modify the zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Thus stealing an NSEC5KEY would only result in the ability to more easily enumerate a zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Due to the messy evolution of the protocol and a desire to preserve backwards compatibility, online DNSSEC signing servers return a "white lie" instead of authenticating a denial of existence directly.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The technique outlined in RFC 4470 returns a NSEC record in which the pairs of domains lexically surround the requested domain.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] For example, request for `k.example.com` would thus result in an NSEC record proving that nothing exists between the (fictitious) domains `j.example.com` and `l.example.com`.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This is also possible with NSEC3 records.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Cloudflare pioneered a pair of alternative approaches, which manage to achieve the same result in one third of the response size.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The first is a variation on the "white lies" approach, called "black lies", which exploits common DNS client behavior to state the nonexistence more compactly.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The second approach instead chooses to prove that "the record exists but the requested record type does not", which they call "DNS shotgun".
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The Internet is critical infrastructure, yet its operation depends on the fundamentally insecure DNS.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Thus, there is strong incentive to secure DNS, and deploying DNSSEC is generally considered to be a critical part of that effort.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] *National Strategy to Secure Cyberspace* specifically identified the need to secure DNS.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Wide-scale deployment of DNSSEC could resolve many other security problems as well, such as secure key distribution for e-mail addresses.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC deployment in large-scale networks is also challenging.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC can be deployed at any level of a DNS hierarchy, but it must be widely available in a zone before many others will want to adopt it.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS servers must be updated with software that supports DNSSEC, and DNSSEC data must be created and added to the DNS zone data.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] A TCP/IP-using client must have their DNS resolver (client) updated before it can use DNSSEC's capabilities.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] What is more, any resolver must have, or have a way to acquire, at least one public key that it can trust before it can start using DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC implementation can add significant load to some DNS servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Common DNSSEC-signed responses are far larger than the default UDP size of 512 bytes.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In theory, this can be handled through multiple IP fragments, but many "middleboxes" in the field do not handle these correctly.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Yet many current TCP implementations store a great deal of data for each TCP connection; heavily loaded servers can run out of resources simply trying to respond to a larger number of (possibly bogus) DNSSEC requests.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Some protocol extensions, such as TCP Cookie Transactions, have been developed to reduce this loading.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] To address these challenges, significant effort is ongoing to deploy DNSSEC, because the Internet is so vital to so many organizations.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] ARIN is also signing their reverse zones.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In February 2007, TDC became the first Swedish ISP to start offering this feature to its customers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] IANA publicly tested a sample signed root since June 2007.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] During this period prior to the production signing of the root, there were also several alternative trust anchors.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The IKS Jena introduced one on January 19, 2006, the Internet Systems Consortium introduced another on March 27 of the same year, while ICANN themselves announced a third on February 17, 2009.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On June 2, 2009, Afilias, the registry service provider for Public Interest Registry's .org zone signed the .org TLD.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Afilias and PIR also detailed on September 26, 2008, that the first phase, involving large registrars it has a strong working relationship with ("friends and family") would be the first to be able to sign their domains, beginning "early 2009".
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On June 23, 2010, 13 registrars were listed as offering DNSSEC records for .ORG domains.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] VeriSign ran a pilot project to allow .com and .net domains to register themselves for the purpose of NSEC3 experimentation.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This goal was achieved on-schedule and Verisign's DNSSEC VP, Matt Larson, won InfoWorld's Technology Leadership Award for 2011 for his role in advancing DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC was first deployed at the root level on July 15, 2010.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This is expected to greatly simplify the deployment of DNSSEC resolvers, since the root trust anchor can be used to validate any DNSSEC zone that has a complete chain of trust from the root.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Since the chain of trust must be traced back to a trusted root without interruption in order to validate, trust anchors must still be configured for secure zones if any of the zones above them are not secure.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] For example, if the zone "signed.example.org" was secured but the "example.org" zone was not, then, even though the ".org" zone and the root are signed, a trust anchor has to be deployed in order to validate the zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In September 2008, ICANN and VeriSign each published implementation proposals and in October, the National Telecommunications and Information Administration (NTIA) asked the public for comments.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] It is unclear if the comments received affected the design of the final deployment plan.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On June 3, 2009, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) announced plans to sign the root by the end of 2009, in conjunction with ICANN, VeriSign and the NTIA.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On October 6, 2009, at the 59th RIPE Conference meeting, ICANN and VeriSign announced the planned deployment timeline for deploying DNSSEC within the root zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] At the meeting it was announced that it would be incrementally deployed to one root name server a month, starting on December 1, 2009, with the final root name server serving a DNSSEC signed zone on July 1, 2010, and the root zone will be signed with a RSA/SHA256 DNSKEY.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] During the incremental roll-out period the root zone will serve a *Deliberately Unvalidatable Root Zone* (DURZ) that uses dummy keys, with the final DNSKEY record not being distributed until July 1, 2010.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This means the keys that were used to sign the zone use are deliberately unverifiable; the reason for this deployment was to monitor changes in traffic patterns caused by the larger responses to queries requesting DNSSEC resource records.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The .org top-level domain was signed with DNSSEC in June 2010, followed by .com, .net, and .edu later in 2010 and 2011.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Country code top-level domains were able to deposit keys starting in May 2010.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of November 2011 more than 25% of top-level domains are signed with DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On January 25, 2010, the L (ell) root server began serving a *Deliberately Unvalidatable Root Zone* (DURZ).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The zone uses signatures of a SHA-2 (SHA-256) hash created using the RSA algorithm, as defined in RFC 5702.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of May 2010, all thirteen root servers began serving the DURZ.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On July 15, 2010, the first root full production DNSSEC root zone was signed, with the SOA serial 2010071501.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Root trust anchors are available from IANA.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Underneath the root there is a large set of top-level domains that must be signed in order to achieve full DNSSEC deployment.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The List of Internet top-level domains provides details about which of the existing top-level domains have been signed and linked to the root.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In March 2006, the Internet Systems Consortium introduced the DNSSEC Lookaside Validation registry.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DLV was intended to make DNSSEC easier to deploy in the absence of a root trust anchor.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] At the time it was imagined that a validator might have to maintain large numbers of trust anchors corresponding to signed subtrees of the DNS.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The purpose of DLV was to allow validators to offload the effort of managing a trust anchor repository to a trusted third party.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DLV registry maintained a central list of trust anchors, instead of each validator repeating the work of maintaining its own list.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] To use DLV, a validator that supports it was needed, such as BIND or Unbound, configured with a trust anchor for a DLV zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This zone contained DLV records; these had exactly the same format as DS records, but instead of referring to a delegated sub-zone, they referred to a zone elsewhere in the DNS tree.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] When the validator could not find a chain of trust from the root to the RRset it is trying to check, it searched for a DLV record that could provide an alternative chain of trust.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Gaps in the chain of trust, such as unsigned top-level domains or registrars that did not support DNSSEC delegations, meant administrators of lower-level domains could use DLV to allow their DNS data to be validated by resolvers which had been configured to use DLV.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This may have hindered DNSSEC deployment by taking pressure off registrars and TLD registries to properly support DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DLV also added complexity by adding more actors and code paths for DNSSEC validation.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] ISC decommissioned its DLV registry in 2017.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DLV support was deprecated in BIND 9.12 and completely removed from BIND 9.16.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Unbound version 1.5.4 (July 2015) marked DLV as decommissioned in the example configuration and manual page.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Knot Resolver and PowerDNS Recursor never implemented DLV.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In March 2020, the IETF published RFC 8749, retiring DLV as a standard and moving RFC 4432 and RFC 5074 to "Historic" status.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The Science and Technology Directorate of the U.S.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Department of Homeland Security (DHS) sponsors the "DNSSEC Deployment Initiative".
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] It was reported that on March 30, 2007, the U.S.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Department of Homeland Security proposed "to have the key to sign the DNS root zone solidly in the hands of the US government." However no U.S.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Government officials were present in the meeting room and the comment that sparked the article was made by another party.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DHS later commented on why they believe others jumped to the false conclusion that the U.S.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Government had made such a proposal: "The U.S.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Department of Homeland Security is funding the development of a technical plan for implementing DNSSec, and last October distributed an initial draft of it to a long list of international experts for comments.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The draft lays out a series of options for who could be the holder, or "operator," of the Root Zone Key, essentially boiling down to a governmental agency or a contractor.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) published NIST Special Publication 800-81 Secure Domain Name System (DNS) Deployment Guide on May 16, 2006, with guidance on how to deploy DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] NIST intended to release new DNSSEC Federal Information Security Management Act (FISMA) requirements in NIST SP800-53-R1, referencing this deployment guide.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] U.S. agencies would then have had one year after final publication of NIST SP800-53-R1 to meet these new FISMA requirements.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] However, at the time NSEC3 had not been completed.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] NIST had suggested using split domains, a technique that is known to be possible but is difficult to deploy correctly, and has the security weaknesses noted above.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On 22 August 2008, the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) released a memorandum requiring U.S.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Federal Agencies to deploy DNSSEC across .gov sites; the .gov root must be signed by January 2009, and all subdomains under .gov must be signed by December 2009.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] While the memo focuses on .gov sites, the U.S.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Defense Information Systems Agency says it intends to meet OMB DNSSEC requirements in the .mil (U.S. military) domain as well.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Several ISPs have started to deploy DNSSEC-validating DNS recursive resolvers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Comcast became the first major ISP to do so in the United States, announcing their intentions on October 18, 2010 and completing deployment on January 11, 2012.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] According to a study at APNIC, the proportion of clients who exclusively use DNS resolvers that perform DNSSEC validation rose to 8.3% in May 2013.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] About half of these clients were using Google's public DNS resolver.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In September 2015, Verisign announced their free public DNS resolver service, and although unmentioned in their press releases, it also performs DNSSEC validation.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] By the beginning of 2016, APNIC's monitoring showed the proportion of clients who exclusively use DNS resolvers that perform DNSSEC validation had increased to about 15%.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Google's public recursive DNS server enabled DNSSEC validation on May 6, 2013.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] BIND, the most popular DNS management software, enables DNSSEC support by default since version 9.5.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The Quad9 public recursive DNS has performed DNSSEC validation on its main 9.9.9.9 address since it was established on May 11, 2016.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Quad9 also provides an alternate service which does not perform DNSSEC validation, principally for debugging.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In September 2023, Microsoft announced it would utilize DNSSEC (via DANE) to verify the authenticity of certificates during SMTP communications.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Geoff Huston has argued that DNSSEC deployment should be given up.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In 2016, email provider Fastmail published a blog post stating that the company does not plan on implementing DNSSEC, referencing the many DNSSEC-related outages that had occurred around the time.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] More positive reactions have been put forward by internet infrastructure corporation Cloudflare, which hired one of the founders of DNSSEC to help implement it at the company.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Domain registry Spaceship (a brand owned by Namecheap) enables DNSSEC automatically for supported domains it hosts the nameservers of.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In 2025, Dutch registry SIDN argued against the claim that DNSSEC is complex when compared to other internet protocols.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC deployment requires software on the server and client side.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The **Domain Name System** (**DNS**) is a hierarchical and distributed name service that provides a naming system for computers, services, and other resources on the Internet or other Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] It associates various information with *domain names* (identification strings) assigned to each of the associated entities.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Most prominently, it translates readily memorized domain names to the numerical IP addresses needed for locating and identifying computer services and devices with the underlying network protocols.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System has been an essential component of the functionality of the Internet since 1985.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System delegates the responsibility of assigning domain names and mapping those names to Internet resources by designating authoritative name servers for each domain.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Network administrators may delegate authority over subdomains of their allocated name space to other name servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This mechanism provides distributed and fault-tolerant service and was designed to avoid a single large central database.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In addition, the DNS specifies the technical functionality of the database service that is at its core.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] It defines the DNS protocol, a detailed specification of the data structures and data communication exchanges used in the DNS, as part of the Internet protocol suite.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The Internet maintains two principal namespaces, the domain name hierarchy and the IP address spaces.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System maintains the domain name hierarchy and provides translation services between it and the address spaces.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Internet name servers and a communication protocol implement the Domain Name System.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A DNS name server is a server that stores the DNS records for a domain; a DNS name server responds with answers to queries against its database.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The most common types of records stored in the DNS database are for start of authority (SOA), IP addresses (A and AAAA), SMTP mail exchangers (MX), name servers (NS), pointers for reverse DNS lookups (PTR), and domain name aliases (CNAME).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Although not intended to be a general-purpose database, DNS has been expanded over time to store records for other types of data for either automatic lookups, such as DNSSEC records, or for human queries such as *responsible person* (RP) records.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] As a general-purpose database, the DNS has also been used in combating unsolicited email (spam) by storing blocklists.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The DNS database is conventionally stored in a structured text file, the zone file, but other database systems are common.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System originally used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) as transport over IP.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Reliability, security, and privacy concerns spawned the use of the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) as well as numerous other protocol developments.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] An often-used analogy to explain the DNS is that it serves as the phone book for the Internet by translating human-friendly computer hostnames into IP addresses.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The DNS can be quickly and transparently updated, allowing a service's location on the network to change without affecting the end users, who continue to use the same hostname.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Users take advantage of this when they use meaningful Uniform Resource Locators (URLs) and e-mail addresses without having to know how the computer actually locates the services.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] An important and ubiquitous function of the DNS is its central role in distributed Internet services such as cloud services and content delivery networks.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] When a user accesses a distributed Internet service using a URL, the domain name of the URL is translated to the IP address of a server that is proximal to the user.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The key functionality of the DNS exploited here is that different users can *simultaneously* receive different translations for the *same* domain name, a key point of divergence from a traditional phone-book view of the DNS.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This process of using the DNS to assign proximal servers to users is key to providing faster and more reliable responses on the Internet and is widely used by most major Internet services.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The DNS reflects the structure of administrative responsibility on the Internet.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Each subdomain is a zone of administrative autonomy delegated to a manager.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] For zones operated by a registry, administrative information is often complemented by the registry's RDAP and WHOIS services.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] That data can be used to gain insight on, and track responsibility for, a given host on the Internet.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Using a simpler, more memorable name in place of a host's numerical address dates back to the ARPANET era.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The Stanford Research Institute (now SRI International) maintained a text file named HOSTS.TXT that mapped host names to the numerical addresses of computers on the ARPANET.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Elizabeth Feinler developed and maintained the first ARPANET directory.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Maintenance of numerical addresses, called the Assigned Numbers List, was handled by Jon Postel at the University of Southern California's Information Sciences Institute (ISI), whose team worked closely with SRI.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Computers, including their hostnames and addresses, were added to the primary file by contacting the SRI Network Information Center (NIC), directed by Feinler, via telephone during business hours.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Later, Feinler set up a WHOIS directory on a server in the NIC for retrieval of information about resources, contacts, and entities.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] She and her team developed the concept of domains.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Feinler suggested that domains should be based on the location of the physical address of the computer.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Computers at educational institutions would have the domain *edu*, for example.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] She and her team managed the Host Naming Registry from 1972 to 1989.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] By the early 1980s, maintaining a single, centralized host table had become slow and unwieldy and the emerging network required an automated naming system to address technical and personnel issues.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Postel directed the task of forging a compromise between five competing proposals of solutions to Paul Mockapetris.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Mockapetris instead created the Domain Name System in 1983 while at the University of Southern California.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The Internet Engineering Task Force published the original specifications in RFC 882 and RFC 883 in November 1983.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] These were updated in RFC 973 in January 1986.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In 1984, four UC Berkeley students, Douglas Terry, Mark Painter, David Riggle, and Songnian Zhou, wrote the first Unix name server implementation for the Berkeley Internet Name Domain, commonly referred to as BIND.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In 1985, Kevin Dunlap of DEC substantially revised the DNS implementation.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Mike Karels, Phil Almquist, and Paul Vixie then took over BIND maintenance.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Internet Systems Consortium was founded in 1994 by Rick Adams, Paul Vixie, and Carl Malamud, expressly to provide a home for BIND development and maintenance.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] BIND versions from 4.9.3 onward were developed and maintained by ISC, with support provided by ISC's sponsors.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] As co-architects/programmers, Bob Halley and Paul Vixie released the first production-ready version of BIND version 8 in May 1997.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Since 2000, over 43 different core developers have worked on BIND.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In November 1987, RFC 1034 and RFC 1035 superseded the 1983 DNS specifications.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Several additional Request for Comments have proposed extensions to the core DNS protocols.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The domain name space consists of a tree data structure.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Each node or leaf in the tree has a *label* and zero or more *resource records* (RR), which hold information associated with the domain name.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The domain name itself consists of the label, concatenated with the name of its parent node on the right, separated by a dot.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The tree sub-divides into *zones* beginning at the root zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A DNS zone may consist of as many domains and subdomains as the zone manager chooses.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNS can also be partitioned according to *class* where the separate classes can be thought of as an array of parallel namespace trees.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Administrative responsibility for any zone may be divided by creating additional zones.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Authority over the new zone is said to be *delegated* to a designated name server.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The parent zone ceases to be authoritative for the new zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The definitive descriptions of the rules for forming domain names appear in RFC 1035, RFC 1123, RFC 2181, and RFC 5892.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A domain name consists of one or more parts, technically called *labels*, that are conventionally concatenated, and delimited by dots, such as example.com.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The right-most label conveys the top-level domain; for example, the domain name www.example.com belongs to the top-level domain *com*.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The hierarchy of domains descends from right to left; each label to the left specifies a subdivision, or subdomain of the domain to the right.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] For example, the label *example* specifies a subdomain of the *com* domain, and *www* is a subdomain of example.com.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This tree of subdivisions may have up to 127 levels.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A label may contain zero to 63 characters, because the length is only allowed to take 6 bits.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The null label of length zero is reserved for the root zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The full domain name may not exceed the length of 253 characters in its textual representation (or 254 with the trailing dot).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In the internal binary representation of the DNS this maximum length of 253 requires 255 octets of storage, as it also stores the length of the first of many labels and adds last null byte.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] 255 length is only achieved with at least 6 labels (counting the last null label).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Although no technical limitation exists to prevent domain name labels from using any character that is representable by an octet, hostnames use a preferred format and character set.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The characters allowed in labels are a subset of the ASCII character set, consisting of characters *a* through *z*, *A* through *Z*, digits *0* through *9*, and hyphen.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This rule is known as the *LDH rule* (letters, digits, hyphen).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Domain names are interpreted in a case-independent manner.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Labels may not start or end with a hyphen.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] An additional rule requires that top-level domain names should not be all-numeric.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The limited set of ASCII characters permitted in the DNS prevented the representation of names and words of many languages in their native alphabets or scripts.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] To make this possible, ICANN approved the Internationalizing Domain Names in Applications (IDNA) system, by which user applications, such as web browsers, map Unicode strings into the valid DNS character set using Punycode.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In 2009, ICANN approved the installation of internationalized domain name country code top-level domains (*ccTLD*s).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In addition, many registries of the existing top-level domain names (*TLD*s) have adopted the IDNA system, guided by RFC 5890, RFC 5891, RFC 5892, RFC 5893.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System is maintained by a distributed database system, which uses the client–server model.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The nodes of this database are the name servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Each domain has at least one authoritative DNS server that publishes information about that domain and the name servers of any domains subordinate to it.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The top of the hierarchy is served by the root name servers, the servers to query when looking up (*resolving*) a TLD.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] An authoritative name server can either be a *primary* server or a *secondary* server.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Historically the terms *master/slave* and *primary/secondary* were sometimes used interchangeably but the current practice is to use the latter form.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A primary server is a server that stores the original copies of all zone records.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A secondary server uses a special automatic updating mechanism in the DNS protocol in communication with its primary to maintain an identical copy of the primary records.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Every DNS zone must be assigned a set of authoritative name servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This set of servers is stored in the parent domain zone with name server (NS) records.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] An authoritative server indicates its status of supplying definitive answers, deemed *authoritative*, by setting a protocol flag, called the "*Authoritative Answer*" (*AA*) bit in its responses.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] When a name server is designated as the authoritative server for a domain name for which it does not have authoritative data, it presents a type of error called a "lame delegation" or "lame response".
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Domain name resolvers determine the domain name servers responsible for the domain name in question by a sequence of queries starting with the right-most (top-level) domain label.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] For proper operation of its domain name resolver, a network host is configured with an initial cache (*hints*) of the known addresses of the root name servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The hints are updated periodically by an administrator by retrieving a dataset from a reliable source.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Assuming the resolver has no cached records to accelerate the process, the resolution process starts with a query to one of the root servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In typical operation, the root servers do not answer directly, but respond with a referral to more authoritative servers, e.g., a query for "www.wikipedia.org" is referred to the *org* servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The resolver now queries the servers referred to, and iteratively repeats this process until it receives an authoritative answer.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The diagram illustrates this process for the host that is named by the fully qualified domain name "www.wikipedia.org".
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This mechanism would place a large traffic burden on the root servers, if every resolution on the Internet required starting at the root.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In practice caching is used in DNS servers to off-load the root servers, and as a result, root name servers actually are involved in only a relatively small fraction of all requests.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In theory, authoritative name servers are sufficient for the operation of the Internet.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] However, with only authoritative name servers operating, every DNS query must start with recursive queries at the root zone of the Domain Name System and each user system would have to implement resolver software capable of recursive operation.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Typically, such caching DNS servers also implement the recursive algorithm necessary to resolve a given name starting with the DNS root through to the authoritative name servers of the queried domain.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] With this function implemented in the name server, user applications gain efficiency in design and operation.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The combination of DNS caching and recursive functions in a name server is not mandatory; the functions can be implemented independently in servers for special purposes.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Internet service providers (ISP) typically provide recursive and caching name servers for their customers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In addition, many home networking routers implement DNS caches and recursion to improve efficiency in the local network.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The client side of the DNS is called a DNS resolver.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A resolver is responsible for initiating and sequencing the queries that ultimately lead to a full resolution (translation) of the resource sought, e.g., translation of a domain name into an IP address.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers are classified by a variety of query methods, such as *recursive*, *non-recursive*, and *iterative*.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A resolution process may use a combination of these methods.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In a *non-recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a DNS server that provides a record either for which the server is authoritative, or it provides a partial result without querying other servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In case of a caching DNS resolver, the non-recursive query of its local DNS cache delivers a result and reduces the load on upstream DNS servers by caching DNS resource records for a period of time after an initial response from upstream DNS servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In a *recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a single DNS server, which may in turn query other DNS servers on behalf of the requester.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] For example, a simple stub resolver running on a home router typically makes a recursive query to the DNS server run by the user's ISP.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A recursive query is one for which the DNS server answers the query completely by querying other name servers as needed.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In typical operation, a client issues a recursive query to a caching recursive DNS server, which subsequently issues non-recursive queries to determine the answer and send a single answer back to the client.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The resolver, or another DNS server acting recursively on behalf of the resolver, negotiates use of recursive service using bits in the query headers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNS servers are not required to support recursive queries.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The *iterative query* procedure is a process in which a DNS resolver queries a chain of one or more DNS servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Each server refers the client to the next server in the chain, until the current server can fully resolve the request.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] For example, a possible resolution of www.example.com would query a global root server, then a "com" server, and finally an "example.com" server.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Name servers in delegations are identified by name, rather than by IP address.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This means that a resolving name server must issue another DNS request to discover the IP address of the server to which it has been referred.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] If the name given in the delegation is a subdomain of the domain for which the delegation is being provided, there is a circular dependency.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In this case, the name server providing the delegation must also provide one or more IP addresses for the authoritative name server mentioned in the delegation.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The delegating name server provides this glue in the form of records in the *additional section* of the DNS response, and provides the delegation in the *authority section* of the response.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A glue record is a combination of the name server and IP address.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] For example, if the authoritative name server for example.org is ns1.example.org, a computer trying to resolve www.example.org first resolves ns1.example.org.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] As ns1 is contained in example.org, this requires resolving example.org first, which presents a circular dependency.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] To break the dependency, the name server for the top level domain org includes glue along with the delegation for example.org.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The glue records are address records that provide IP addresses for ns1.example.org.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The resolver uses one or more of these IP addresses to query one of the domain's authoritative servers, which allows it to complete the DNS query.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A common approach to reduce the query load on DNS servers is to cache the results of name resolution locally or on intermediary resolver hosts.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Each DNS query result comes with a time to live (TTL), which indicates how long the information remains valid before it needs to be discarded or refreshed.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This TTL is determined by the administrator of the authoritative DNS server and can range from a few seconds to several days or even weeks.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] As a result of this distributed caching architecture, changes to DNS records do not propagate throughout the network immediately, but require all caches to expire and to be refreshed after the TTL.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] RFC 1912 conveys basic rules for determining appropriate TTL values.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Some resolvers may override TTL values, as the protocol supports caching for up to sixty-eight years or no caching at all.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Negative caching, i.e. the caching of the fact of non-existence of a record, is determined by name servers authoritative for a zone which must include the Start of Authority (SOA) record when reporting no data of the requested type exists.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The value of the *minimum* field of the SOA record and the TTL of the SOA itself is used to establish the TTL for the negative answer.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A reverse DNS lookup is a query of the DNS for domain names when the IP address is known.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Multiple domain names may be associated with an IP address.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The DNS stores IP addresses in the form of domain names as specially formatted names in pointer (PTR) records within the infrastructure top-level domain arpa.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] For IPv6, the reverse lookup domain is ip6.arpa.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The IP address is represented as a name in reverse-ordered octet representation for IPv4, and reverse-ordered nibble representation for IPv6.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] When performing a reverse lookup, the DNS client converts the address into these formats before querying the name for a PTR record following the delegation chain as for any DNS query.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] For example, assuming the IPv4 address 208.80.152.2 is assigned to Wikimedia, it is represented as a DNS name in reverse order: 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] When the DNS resolver gets a pointer (PTR) request, it begins by querying the root servers, which point to the servers of American Registry for Internet Numbers (ARIN) for the 208.in-addr.arpa zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] ARIN's servers delegate 152.80.208.in-addr.arpa to Wikimedia to which the resolver sends another query for 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa, which results in an authoritative response.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Users generally do not communicate directly with a DNS resolver.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Instead DNS resolution takes place transparently in applications such as web browsers, e-mail clients, and other Internet applications.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] When an application makes a request that requires a domain name lookup, such programs send a resolution request to the DNS resolver in the local operating system, which in turn handles the communications required.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The DNS resolver will almost invariably have a cache (see above) containing recent lookups.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] If the cache can provide the answer to the request, the resolver will return the value in the cache to the program that made the request.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] If the cache does not contain the answer, the resolver will send the request to one or more designated DNS servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In any event, the name server thus queried will follow the process outlined above, until it either successfully finds a result or does not.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] It then returns its results to the DNS resolver; assuming it has found a result, the resolver duly caches that result for future use, and hands the result back to the software which initiated the request.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Some large ISPs have configured their DNS servers to violate rules, such as by disobeying TTLs, or by indicating that a domain name does not exist just because one of its name servers does not respond.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Some applications such as web browsers maintain an internal DNS cache to avoid repeated lookups via the network.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This practice can add extra difficulty when debugging DNS issues as it obscures the history of such data.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] These caches typically use very short caching times on the order of one minute.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer represents a notable exception: versions up to IE 3.x cache DNS records for 24 hours by default.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer 4.x and later versions (up to IE 8) decrease the default timeout value to half an hour, which may be changed by modifying the default configuration.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] When Google Chrome detects issues with the DNS server it displays a specific error message.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System includes several other functions and features.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Hostnames and IP addresses are not required to match in a one-to-one relationship.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Multiple hostnames may correspond to a single IP address, which is useful in virtual hosting, in which many web sites are served from a single host.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Alternatively, a single hostname may resolve to many IP addresses to facilitate fault tolerance and load distribution to multiple server instances across an enterprise or the global Internet.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNS serves other purposes in addition to translating names to IP addresses.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] For instance, mail transfer agents use DNS to find the best mail server to deliver e-mail: An MX record provides a mapping between a domain and a mail exchanger; this can provide an additional layer of fault tolerance and load distribution.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The DNS is used for efficient storage and distribution of IP addresses of block-listed email hosts.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A common method is to place the IP address of the subject host into the sub-domain of a higher level domain name, and to resolve that name to a record that indicates a positive or a negative indication.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] E-mail servers can query blocklist.example to find out if a specific host connecting to them is in the block list.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Many such block lists, either subscription-based or free of cost, are available for use by email administrators and anti-spam software.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] To provide resilience in the event of computer or network failure, multiple DNS servers are usually provided for coverage of each domain.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] At the top level of global DNS, thirteen groups of root name servers exist, with additional "copies" of them distributed worldwide via anycast addressing.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS (DDNS) updates a DNS server with a client IP address on-the-fly, for example, when moving between ISPs or mobile hot spots, or when the IP address changes administratively.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The DNS protocol uses two types of DNS messages, queries and responses; both have the same format.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Each message consists of a header and four sections: question, answer, authority, and an additional space.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A header field (*flags*) controls the content of these four sections.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The header section consists of the following fields: *Identification*, *Flags*, *Number of questions*, *Number of answers*, *Number of authority resource records* (RRs), and *Number of additional RRs*.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Each field is 16 bits long, and appears in the order given.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The identification field is used to match responses with queries.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] After the flags word, the header ends with four 16-bit integers which contain the number of records in each of the sections that follow, in the same order.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Indicates if the message is a query (0) or a reply (1).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The type can be QUERY (standard query, 0), IQUERY (inverse query, 1), or STATUS (server status request, 2).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Authoritative Answer, in a response, indicates if the DNS server is authoritative for the queried hostname.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] TrunCation, indicates that this message was truncated due to excessive length.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Recursion Desired, indicates if the client means a recursive query.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Recursion Available, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server supports recursion.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Authentic Data, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server verified the data.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Checking Disabled, in a query, indicates that non-verified data is acceptable in a response.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Response code, can be NOERROR (0), FORMERR (1, Format error), SERVFAIL (2), NXDOMAIN (3, Nonexistent domain), etc.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The question section has a simpler format than the resource record format used in the other sections.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The domain name is broken into discrete labels which are concatenated; each label is prefixed by the length of that label.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System specifies a database of information elements for network resources.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The types of information elements are categorized and organized with a list of DNS record types, the resource records (RRs).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Each record has a type (name and number), an expiration time (time to live), a class, and type-specific data.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Resource records of the same type are described as a *resource record set* (RRset), having no special ordering.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers return the entire set upon query, but servers may implement round-robin ordering to achieve load balancing.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In contrast, the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) work on the complete set of resource record in canonical order.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The *CLASS* of a record is set to IN (for *Internet*) for common DNS records involving Internet hostnames, servers, or IP addresses.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In addition, the classes Chaos (CH) and Hesiod (HS) exist.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Each class is an independent name space with potentially different delegations of DNS zones.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In addition to resource records defined in a zone file, the domain name system also defines several request types that are used only in communication with other DNS nodes (*on the wire*), such as when performing zone transfers (AXFR/IXFR) or for EDNS (OPT).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The domain name system supports wildcard DNS records which specify names that start with the *asterisk label*, `*`, e.g., `*.example`.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNS records belonging to wildcard domain names specify rules for generating resource records within a single DNS zone by substituting whole labels with matching components of the query name, including any specified descendants.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] For example, in the following configuration, the DNS zone *x.example* specifies that all subdomains, including subdomains of subdomains, of *x.example* use the mail exchanger (MX) *a.x.example*.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The AAAA record for *a.x.example* is needed to specify the mail exchanger IP address.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] As this has the result of excluding this domain name and its subdomains from the wildcard matches, an additional MX record for the subdomain *a.x.example*, as well as a wildcarded MX record for all of its subdomains, must also be defined in the DNS zone.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The role of wildcard records was refined in RFC 4592, because the original definition in RFC 1034 was incomplete and resulted in misinterpretations by implementers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The original DNS protocol had limited provisions for extension with new features.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In 1999, Paul Vixie published in RFC 2671 (superseded by RFC 6891) an extension mechanism, called Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS) that introduced optional protocol elements without increasing overhead when not in use.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This was accomplished through the OPT pseudo-resource record that only exists in wire transmissions of the protocol, but not in any zone files.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Initial extensions were also suggested (EDNS0), such as increasing the DNS message size in UDP datagrams.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS updates use the UPDATE DNS opcode to add or remove resource records dynamically from a zone database maintained on an authoritative DNS server.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This facility is useful to register network clients into the DNS when they boot or become otherwise available on the network.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] As a booting client may be assigned a different IP address each time from a DHCP server, it is not possible to provide static DNS assignments for such clients.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] From the time of its origin in 1983 the DNS has used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) for transport over IP.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Its limitations have motivated numerous protocol developments for reliability, security, privacy, and other criteria, in the following decades.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] UDP reserves port number 53 for servers listening to queries.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Such a query consists of a clear-text request sent in a single UDP packet from the client, responded to with a clear-text reply sent in a single UDP packet from the server.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] When the length of the answer exceeds 512 bytes and both client and server support Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS), larger UDP packets may be used.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Use of DNS over UDP is limited by, among other things, its lack of transport-layer encryption, authentication, reliable delivery, and message length.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In 1989, RFC 1123 specified optional Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) transport for DNS queries, replies and, particularly, zone transfers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Via fragmentation of long replies, TCP allows longer responses, reliable delivery, and re-use of long-lived connections between clients and servers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] For larger responses, the server refers the client to TCP transport.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNS over TLS emerged as an IETF standard for encrypted DNS in 2016, utilizing Transport Layer Security (TLS) to protect the entire connection, rather than just the DNS payload.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] RFC 7858 specifies that opportunistic encryption and authenticated encryption may be supported, but did not make either server or client authentication mandatory.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNS over HTTPS was developed as a competing standard for DNS query transport in 2018, tunneling DNS query data over HTTPS, which transports HTTP over TLS.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DoH was promoted as a more web-friendly alternative to DNS since, like DNSCrypt, it uses TCP port 443, and thus looks similar to web traffic, though they are easily differentiable in practice without proper padding.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] RFC 9250, published in 2022 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over QUIC.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] It has "privacy properties similar to DNS over TLS (DoT) [...], and latency characteristics similar to classic DNS over UDP".
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This method is not the same as DNS over HTTP/3.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] RFC 9953, published in 2026 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over CoAP.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The "application use case of DoC is inspired by DNS over HTTPS (DoH) (RFC 8484).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] However, DoC aims for deployment in the constrained Internet of Things (IoT), which usually conflicts with the requirements introduced by HTTPS." DoC outperforms other DNS resolution mechanisms in constrained scenarios.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Oblivious DNS (ODNS) was invented and implemented by researchers at Princeton University and the University of Chicago as an extension to unencrypted DNS, before DoH was standardized and widely deployed.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] ODoH combines ingress/egress separation (invented in ODNS) with DoH's HTTPS tunneling and TLS transport-layer encryption in a single protocol.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNS may be run over virtual private networks (VPNs) and tunneling protocols.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The privacy gains of Oblivious DNS can be garnered through the use of the preexisting Tor network of ingress and egress nodes, paired with the transport-layer encryption provided by TLS.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt uses either TCP port 443, the same port as HTTPS encrypted web traffic, or UDP port 443.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This introduced not only privacy regarding the content of the query, but also a significant measure of firewall-traversal capability.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Privacy of user/query pairs is created, since the ingress node does not know the content of the query, while the egress node does not know the identity of the client.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt was first implemented in production by OpenDNS in December 2011.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] There are several free and open source software implementations that additionally integrate ODoH.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] It is available for a variety of operating systems, including Unix, Apple iOS, Linux, Android, and Windows.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Originally, security concerns were not major design considerations for DNS software or any software for deployment on the early Internet, as the network was not open for participation by the general public.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] However, the expansion of the Internet into the commercial sector in the 1990s changed the requirements for security measures to protect data integrity and user authentication.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Several vulnerability issues were discovered and exploited by malicious users.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] One such issue is DNS cache poisoning, in which data is distributed to caching resolvers under the pretense of being an authoritative origin server, thereby polluting the data store with potentially false information and long expiration times (time-to-live).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Subsequently, legitimate application requests may be redirected to network hosts operated with malicious intent.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNS responses traditionally do not have a cryptographic signature, leading to many attack possibilities; the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) modify DNS to add support for cryptographically signed responses.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNSCurve has been proposed as an alternative to DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Other extensions, such as TSIG, add support for cryptographic authentication between trusted peers and are commonly used to authorize zone transfer or dynamic update operations.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Techniques such as forward-confirmed reverse DNS can also be used to help validate DNS results.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNS can also "leak" from otherwise secure or private connections, if attention is not paid to their configuration, and at times DNS has been used to bypass firewalls by malicious persons, and exfiltrate data, since it is often seen as innocuous.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Some domain names may be used to achieve spoofing effects.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] For example, paypal.com and paypa1.com are different names, yet users may be unable to distinguish them in a graphical user interface depending on the user's chosen typeface.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In many fonts the letter *l* and the numeral *1* look very similar or even identical.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This problem, known as the IDN homograph attack, is acute in systems that support internationalized domain names, as many character codes in ISO 10646 may appear identical on typical computer screens.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This vulnerability is occasionally exploited in phishing.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger is a type of cyber attack technique that uses the DNS to communicate and control malware remotely without relying on conventional protocols that might raise red flags.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The DNSMessenger attack is covert because DNS is primarily used for domain name resolution and is often not closely monitored by network security tools, making it an effective channel for attackers to exploit.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This technique involves the use of DNS TXT records to send commands to infected systems.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Once malware has been surreptitiously installed on a victim's machine, it reaches out to a controlled domain to retrieve commands encoded in DNS text records.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This form of malware communication is stealthy, as DNS requests are usually allowed through firewalls, and because DNS traffic is often seen as benign, these communications can bypass many network security defenses.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger attacks can enable a wide array of malicious activities, from data exfiltration to the delivery of additional payloads, all while remaining under the radar of traditional network security measures.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Understanding and defending against such methods are crucial for maintaining robust cybersecurity.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Originally designed as a public, hierarchical, distributed and heavily cached database, the DNS protocol has no confidentiality controls.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] User queries and nameserver responses are sent unencrypted, enabling network packet sniffing, DNS hijacking, DNS cache poisoning and man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] This deficiency is commonly used by cybercriminals and network operators for marketing purposes, user authentication on captive portals and censorship.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] User privacy is further exposed by proposals for increasing the level of client IP information in DNS queries (RFC 7871) for the benefit of content delivery networks.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Solutions preventing DNS inspection by the local network operator have been criticized for thwarting corporate network security policies and Internet censorship.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Public DNS servers are also criticized for contributing to the centralization of the Internet by placing control over DNS resolution in the hands of the few large companies which can afford to run public resolvers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The right to use a domain name is delegated by domain name registrars which are accredited by the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICANN) or other organizations such as OpenNIC, that are charged with overseeing the name and number systems of the Internet.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In addition to ICANN, each top-level domain (TLD) is maintained and serviced technically by an administrative organization, operating a registry.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A *registry* is responsible for operating the database of names within its authoritative zone, although the term is most often used for TLDs.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] A *registrant* is a person or organization who asked for domain registration.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The registry receives registration information from each domain name *registrar*, which is authorized (accredited) to assign names in the corresponding zone and publishes the information using the WHOIS protocol.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] As of 2015, usage of RDAP is being considered.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] ICANN publishes the complete list of TLDs, TLD registries, and domain name registrars.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Registrant information associated with domain names is maintained in an online database accessible with the WHOIS service.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] For most of the more than 290 country code top-level domains (ccTLDs), the domain registries maintain the WHOIS (Registrant, name servers, expiration dates, etc.) information.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] For instance, DENIC, Germany NIC, holds the DE domain data.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] From about 2001, most generic top-level domain (gTLD) registries have adopted this so-called *thick* registry approach, i.e. keeping the WHOIS data in central registries instead of registrar databases.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] For top-level domains on COM and NET, a *thin* registry model is used.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The domain registry (GoDaddy, BigRock and PDR, VeriSign, etc.) holds basic WHOIS data (i.e., registrar and name servers, etc.).
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] On the other hand, organizations, i.e., registrants using ORG, are on the Public Interest Registry exclusively.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] Some domain name registries, often called *network information centers* (NIC), also function as registrars to end-users, in addition to providing access to the WHOIS datasets.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The top-level domain registries, such as for the domains COM, NET, and ORG use a registry-registrar model consisting of many domain name registrars.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] In this method of management, the registry only manages the domain name database and the relationship with the registrars.
[src:dns-security-extensions/domain-name-system] The *registrants* (users of a domain name) are customers of the registrar, in some cases through additional subcontracting of resellers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:dns-security-extensions/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
